{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646304"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18169"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10883"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25311"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following thoracic vertebrae has one whole facet for rib articulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T1","T2","T5","T9","T10"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thoracic vertebrae are unique in that they articulate with the ribs. Most thoracic vertebrae have two demi-facets on each side for rib articulation, one on the superior aspect and one on the inferior aspect. However, \u003Cstrong\u003ET10\u003C/strong\u003E has one whole facet on each side for articulation with the tenth rib. This is because the tenth rib does not articulate with the vertebra above it, unlike ribs 2 through 9, which articulate with two adjacent vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1\u003C/strong\u003E has a whole facet for the first rib and a demi-facet for the second rib.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2\u003C/strong\u003E through \u003Cstrong\u003ET8\u003C/strong\u003E have two demi-facets for articulation with the ribs above and below.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET9\u003C/strong\u003E may have a whole facet or a demi-facet, depending on the individual, but it is not consistent like T10.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET11\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ET12\u003C/strong\u003E have whole facets for their respective ribs, but they are not the only vertebrae with this feature, as T10 also has a whole facet.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The T10 vertebra has one whole facet for rib articulation.","Understanding vertebral anatomy is crucial for identifying rib articulations."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T22:56:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T22:57:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10883"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data